 of the early Muslim sources but also the many non-Arabic sources, contemporaneous or near-contemporaneous with the conquests. In God's Path begins with a broad picture of the Late Antique world prior to the Prophet's arrival, a world dominated by two superpowers: Byzantium and Sasanian Persia. In between these empires, emerged a distinct Arabian identity, which helped forge the inhabitants of western Arabia into a formidable fighting force. The Arabs are the principal actors in this drama yet, as Hoyland shows, the peoples along the edges of Byzantium and Persia -- the Khazars, Bulgars, Avars, and Turks -- all played critical roles in the remaking of the old world order. The new faith propagated by Muhammad and his successors made it possible for many of the conquered peoples to join the Arabs in creating the first Islamic Empire.  a16 23 0aIslamic EmpirexHistoryy622-661. 0aIslamic EmpirexHistoryy661-750. 0aAncient warfare and civilization.  aDS 38.1 H688 2015wLCc1i0162035242872d4/8/2017e1/11/2017lON_SHELFmUAAUGn5p$150.00rYsYtBOOKu2/26/2015  aDS 38.1 H688 2015wLCc1i32860001071918d11/23/2016e10/24/2016lON_SHELFmBURMANn6rYsYtBOOKu9/8/201501ahttp://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n97047912bhttp://viaf.org/viaf/116219062